metatab-latest: This file contains the raw data for all public school districts, private schools, and charter schools (SFAs) that completed the 2015 USDA Farm to School Census. Results can also be found online at https://farmtoschoolcensus.fns.usda.gov.

column7: This file contains state, territory, and national level summary statistics for those public school districts, private schools, and charter schools (SFAs) that completed the 2015 USDA Farm to School Census.
The state level CCD estimates tab summarizes the number of schools and students participating in farm to school activities using the Common Core of Data.
The state level dollar estimates tab summarizes the dollars spent on all food and local food (including and excluding fluid milk).
2015 Farm to School Census Repondent Data (Updated 10/31/16)

column4: Home page for the Farm To School Census Program.
Detailed of the survey design, data collection and links to datasets.
Documentation for the variables linked from the Common Core of Data.

metatab-latest: The QuestionSource, Universe, Definition, CodesNotes and QuestionText properties in the schema are taken from the datasets 'Variable Map” data file
However, the variable map diverges from the column headers after colum 223. The remaining columns are from the Common Core of Data.
The  file includes matched data from the Common Core of Data (school year 2013-2014) found at https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/pubagency.asp.

The variable map tab describes the coding for each of variables created from the Census data and select variables from the Common Core of Data. All variables matched from the Common Core of Data are described at https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/pdf/2015147_2013-14_LEA_documentation_v1a.pdf.
For detailed information about how this data was collected and analyzed, please visit https://farmtoschoolcensus.fns.usda.gov/about.
All of the data are self-reported and may conflict with other data sources.
If you have questions about the data file or plan to use the data to complete additional analysis, please contact Matthew Benson at matthew.benson@fns.usda.gov.

For the  state_census file, the totcost, totdolinclmilk, totdolexclmilk are included in the variable map, but these varibles are actually part of the state_dollar data schema. This files columns diverge from the Variable map after the pctinterstate
variable.

This file contains state, territory, and national level summary statistics for those public school districts, private schools, and charter schools (SFAs) that completed the 2015 USDA Farm to School Census.
All of the respondent data are self-reported and may conflict with other data sources.
For detailed information about how this data was collected and analyzed, please visit https://farmtoschoolcensus.fns.usda.gov/about.
If you have questions about the data file or plan to use the data to complete additional analysis, please contact Matthew Benson at matthew.benson@fns.usda.gov.
The state level CCD estimates tab summarizes the number of schools and students participating in farm to school activities using the Common Core of Data.
The state level dollar estimates tab summarizes the dollars spent on all food and local food (including and excluding fluid milk).
The variable map tab describes the coding for each of variables created from the Census data.

column8: Conducts farm to school activities
column9:
1= Yes   
2= No, but started activities in 2014-2015 school year   
3= No, but plan to start activities in the future     
4= No activities currently and no plans
column10:
Farm to school activities generally center around procurement of local or regional foods and food,
agriculture or nutrition-based educational activities such as but not limited to:
* Serving local food products in school (meals and snacks) * Serving local food products in classrooms (snacks, taste tests, educational tools) * Conducting educational activities related to local foods such as farmers in the classroom and
culinary education focused on local foods, field trips to farms, farmers' markets or food processing facilities, and educational sessions for parents and community members * Creating and tending school gardens (growing edible fruits and vegetables) Based on the definition above, did your district or any schools in your district participate in farm to school activities during the 2013-2014 school year? (Please check one.) *
